{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-entry-js","path":"/notes/ml/deep_learning/regularization_intuition","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Intuition behind Regularization"},"html":"<h3>Motivating Regularization for Overfitting</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Roughly speaking, weights are usually relatively smaller for a model with a large amount of bias (i.e. underfitting)</li>\n<li>Roughly speaking, weights are usually relatively larger for a model with a large amount of variance (i.e. overfitting)</li>\n<li>Regularization attempts to find a happy medium so the weights don't become too large or too small</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/c82c76d994597b5b27d963047bc72967/regularization_overfitting.svg\" alt=\"regularization\"></p>\n<ul>\n<li>We expect our weights to converge to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> when there is a lot of noise, and our weights to stray from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> when there is signal</li>\n<li>By adding regularization to our model, we are adding some amount of noise that is proportional to our weight</li>\n<li>Since noise makes it harder to pick up on any signal, our data becomes harder to fit as we add more noise</li>\n<li>Therefore, it becomes harder to overfit</li>\n<li>We can control the amount of noise added to our weight by increasing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>Increasing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> will shrink the weights to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> at a faster rate</li>\n<li>It will take longer for our weight to shrink to zero if our weight is already large, compared to if our weight is small</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Illustrating Effects of Regularization</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Up until this point, we know how our penalty terms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∥</mi><mi>w</mi><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∥</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Vert w \\Vert_{1}^{2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.064108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∥</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">∥</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4518920000000004em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.24810799999999997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∥</mi><mi>w</mi><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∥</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Vert w \\Vert_{2}^{2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.064108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∥</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">∥</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4518920000000004em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.24810799999999997em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> lead to shrinkage</li>\n<li>However, we're still probably wondering how exactly shrinkage prevents overfitting</li>\n<li>As hinted at previously, if we increase our regularization parameter <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span>, our weights start to converge to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>Increasing our regularization parameter will leads to more weights becoming equal to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>This zeroes out the impact of our hidden units</li>\n<li>Meaning, our neural network becomes simplified and smaller</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/222c4f49bd82c89573a368e71ce49274/regularization_zero_weights.svg\" alt=\"regularization\"></p>\n<ul>\n<li>In practice, these hidden units aren't actually zeroed out</li>\n<li>Instead, they are still used, but have a much smaller effect</li>\n<li>Therefore, we do in fact end up with a simpler network that has the same effect as if we had a smaller network</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Another Illustration of Regularization Effects</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>If we increase the regularization parameter <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span>, then the weights decrease towards <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>This will prevent overfitting, but could cause underfitting if we increase our regularization parameter <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> too much</li>\n<li>We can notice this issue by taking a closer look at the tanh activation function in our network</li>\n<li>Let's say we're faced with the following:</li>\n</ul>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mi>l</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>w</mi><mi>l</mi></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>l</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">z^{l} = w^{l}a^{l-1} + b^{l}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9824379999999999em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>z</mi><mi>l</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a^{l} = tanh(z^{l})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.149108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8991079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span>\n<ul>\n<li>We know that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> increases by too much, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>w</mi><mi>l</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">w^{l}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.849108em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> will become very small</li>\n<li>Ignoring the effects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>l</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b^{l}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.849108em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, we can see that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mi>l</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">z^{l}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.849108em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> will become very small and will take on a small range of values</li>\n<li>Then, the output <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a^{l}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.849108em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of our tanh function will become relatively linear</li>\n<li>Consequently, linear functions are typically too general and aren't able to fit those complicated, nonlinear decision boundaries we're most likely looking for</li>\n<li>This intuition is true for many other activation functions other than the tanh activation function</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/d5f3ac7fc3cb61ba3653c5f7cac4ac15/regularization_tanh.svg\" alt=\"tanhregularization\"></p>\n<hr>\n<h3>tldr</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Roughly speaking, weights are usually relatively smaller for a model with a large amount of bias (i.e. underfitting)</li>\n<li>Roughly speaking, weights are usually relatively larger for a model with a large amount of variance (i.e. overfitting)</li>\n<li>Regularization attempts to find a happy medium so the weights don't become too large or too small</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>References</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NyG-7nRpsW8&#x26;list=PLkDaE6sCZn6Hn0vK8co82zjQtt3T2Nkqc&#x26;index=5\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Why Regularization Reduces Overfitting</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/59517929/how-does-adding-noise-to-output-avoid-overfitting-on-training-points\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">How Adding Noise Prevents Overfitting</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/213325/neural-network-meaning-of-weights\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Meaning of Weights</a></li>\n</ul>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"ml/deep_learning/regularization_intuition","previousSlug":"ml/deep_learning/regularization","nextSlug":"ml/deep_learning/dropout_regularization","previousTitle":"Regularization","nextTitle":"Dropout Regularization"}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}